{
  "card_id": "supply_and_demand_zones",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Supply and Demand Zones",
  "aliases": [
    "Demand Area",
    "Demand Zone",
    "Supply Area",
    "Supply Zone"
  ],
  "school": "Smart Money Concepts (SMC)",
  "definition": "Price zones where past institutional buying or selling created strong highs or lows, identified by aggressive impulsive moves away from consolidation or a break of structure. The zone is drawn from the candles preceding the impulsive move, typically using the range of the last candle or cluster, and projected forward to act as future support or resistance upon retest.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Locate a sharp, impulsive move away from a price region, often marked by consecutive large-bodied candles in the direction of the move.",
    "Verify an inefficiency, such as a Fair Value Gap (FVG), formed within the impulsive move.",
    "Confirm the impulsive move caused a break of structure (BOS), breaking a prior swing high for demand or swing low for supply.",
    "Ensure the move traveled significantly beyond the zone relative to previous price swings (sufficient push distance).",
    "Mark the zone at the move's origin: include the initiating candle or last opposing candle, any wick rejection, and the full area of aggressive activity.",
    "Assess the higher time frame trend: in a bullish HTF, focus on demand zones at prior support; in a bearish HTF, focus on supply zones at prior resistance or FVG areas.",
    "Validate the zone offers a favorable risk-to-reward ratio with a logical stop-loss placement beyond the zone.",
    "On price revisit, switch to a lower time frame to seek reversal confirmation signals (e.g., RSI divergence, change of character) before entry.",
    "Draw the zone: for the candle or cluster of candles immediately before the impulsive move, draw a rectangle from the highest to lowest point (including wicks) to define the supply/demand zone, and project it forward.",
    "For demand zones, this rectangle covers the range of the last bearish candle(s) before the upsurge; for supply zones, the last bullish candle(s) before the downsurge.",
    "Adjust the zone if price briefly breaks beyond it and reverses (fake out), by extending the zone to include the candles before that break.",
    "When multiple supply/demand shifts occur, update the zone based on the most recent move, incorporating prior reactions.",
    "Wait for price to retrace into the zone and confirm the reversal with a candlestick pattern (e.g., hammer, engulfing) or a momentum candle before entering a trade."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Supply and demand zones serve as high-probability reversal areas. On price return, a rejection confirms entry in the original impulse direction, with a stop-loss beyond the zone. Aligning zones with the higher time frame trend and confirming reversals on lower time frames (e.g., RSI divergence, CHoCH, candlestick patterns) enhances reliability. A decisive break and close beyond the zone signals a change of character, indicating trend reversal. Take-profit targets may be set above the break of structure for longs, or below prior resistance for shorts.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Marking zones based on slow, sideways price action that lacks momentum imbalance.",
    "Drawing zones too narrowly, e.g., using only one candle without including the full aggressive activity area (including wicks).",
    "Ignoring wick rejections that define the actual origin of the move.",
    "Marking every sharp move as a zone without confirming the presence of a fair value gap, break of structure, or sufficient push distance.",
    "Entering a trade immediately upon price touching the zone without waiting for price action confirmation or lower time frame reversal signals.",
    "Using supply/demand zones without first establishing the higher time frame trend bias, risking counter-trend trades.",
    "Assuming every zone break is a valid Change of Character without considering nearby liquidity pools or unfilled FVGs that may invalidate the reversal.",
    "Drawing zones too rigidly without accounting for fake outs (brief breaks beyond the zone before reversing).",
    "Not adjusting zones when newer supply/demand shifts occur, leading to outdated zones.",
    "Choosing the wrong starting point, e.g., ignoring price’s previous reaction to an earlier zone.",
    "Drawing zones from swing highs/lows that have not caused a break of structure (weak highs/lows).",
    "Assuming price will always fully retest the zone; it may reverse before reaching.",
    "Impatience: placing entries before price actually reaches the zone, forcing trades prematurely."
  ],
